Story 1: Create New Branch and Prepare Collector Deployment Files
Description
As a developer, I want to create a new branch with the standard project files and prepare all resources required to deploy the OpenTelemetry Collector using the OTel Operator, so that the deployment artifacts are ready for rollout. This includes creating a new Lightspeed project, populating a new GitHub repo with the required files, modifying configurations for operator-based deployment, and adding Vault annotations.
Business Justification
Preparing a clean deployment baseline ensures consistency, maintainability, and compliance. Creating standardized deployment files ahead of time allows for seamless integration with the OTel Operator and ensures that Vault integration is built in from the start, reducing post-deployment rework.
Acceptance Criteria
 A new Git branch is created following naming conventions (e.g., feature/otel-operator-deployment).
 A new Lightspeed project is created.
 Standard files (README, template YAMLs, values, operator CRDs, etc.) are added to the new GitHub repo.
 Deployment files are updated to be compatible with the Red Hat OTel Operator (Collector CR, autoscaling configs, pipelines, receivers/exporters).
 Vault annotations are added to the Collector CR.
 Configuration passes linting/validation (e.g., oc apply --dry-run).
 Repository contains everything needed to deploy without further structural changes.
Dependencies: None — this is the starting story.

Story 2 (Revised): Coordinate With Tenant Ops and Share Precursor Requirements for Collector Deployment
Description
As a platform engineer, I want to connect with the Tenant Ops team and provide them with all required information, prerequisites, and instructions needed to prepare the cluster for the OTel Collector deployment. This includes sharing the operator installation requirements, permissions, and configuration expectations. This story covers my communication, documentation, and coordination activities only. It will be closed once I have shared the required details and completed my part, regardless of whether Tenant Ops finishes the installation.
Business Justification
Documenting and sharing prerequisite requirements is essential for enabling the Tenant Ops team to set up the environment correctly. Capturing this effort allows tracking of time spent, communication history, and the steps involved, ensuring transparency and traceability for compliance, audits, and CAP-related reporting.
Acceptance Criteria
 A meeting, chat, or email thread is initiated with Tenant Ops.
 A clear list of prerequisites for deploying the OTel Collector is prepared and shared, including:
OTel Operator installation requirements
Required namespaces and permissions
Any SCC/RBAC adjustments
Vault annotation requirements (if applicable)
CRDs that must exist (Collector, TargetAllocator, etc.)
 Documentation or instructions are shared via the agreed channel (Teams, email, Jira comment, Confluence, etc.).
 Any questions from Tenant Ops are answered or clarified.
 Notes or summary of activities are added to the story for audit and CAP tracking.
 Story can be closed regardless of whether the operator is installed by Tenant Ops.

✅ Story 3: Deploy Collector, Troubleshoot, Document Findings, and Submit for BISO Review
Description
As a DevOps engineer, I want to deploy the OTel Collector using the operator and validate functionality, troubleshoot any issues, and document findings. Once validated, I will submit the documentation to the BISO team to support closure of the CAP.
Business Justification
Deploying and validating the collector ensures the environment is compliant and meets CAP requirements. Troubleshooting and documenting findings provides transparency and ensures security and platform teams (including BISO) have the information needed for review and compliance verification.
Acceptance Criteria
 Collector is deployed in the development cluster using the prepared deployment files.
 All pods reach Running state with no CrashLoopBackOff.
 Vault injection is successful and secrets are retrievable.
 Logs confirm successful operator reconciliation and collector startup.
 Any deployment issues are diagnosed, fixed, and re-tested.
 A deployment findings document is created (steps, screenshots, errors, fixes, validation results).
 Documentation is shared with the BISO team for CAP review.
Dependencies:
Depends on Story 1 (deployment files ready).
Depends on Story 2 (operator installed + cluster ready).
